english:
  title: Hall of Reverent Shadow
  author: Lee U
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Where I exist, there form must be;
    My shadow splits my shape in two.
    Yin and yang alternate their play—
    Now hidden, now revealed anew.
    Movement and stillness intertwine,
    Inseparable as breath and bone.

    A hundred deeds fill every day,
    Each one you mimic, trace, and own.
    Left and right, you cleave to me—
    Impossible to fool or hide.
    Should caution dwell in solitude?
    No—even in the darkest room,
    Where light cannot its rays extend,
    You shine as bright as noon's full bloom.

    I turn to face you, heart alert,
    And in that gaze, I turn within.
    Tend the root, preserve the seed—
    Where self begins and ends, begin.
    Hear these words, though I speak low;
    Remember them in silence deep.
    My body casts but empty shade,
    While you the truer vigil keep.

    Within these walls we dance as one,
    You leading me where I must go.
    All day my eyes are fixed on you—
    The shadow is my teacher now.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The 'shadow' (影) serves as a metaphor for conscience or the watched self—an ever-present witness to one's actions.
  - key: ''
    value: This poem reflects neo-Confucian thought on self-cultivation and the internalized gaze of moral awareness.
